Results:

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Signature matching: conformance check now validates param names, param types,
    and return type between spec and impl. The receiver (this) is excluded from comparison.]
  [#*: #+ Borrow locking: assigning a protocol instance (#~"r: f.myreader") takes an
    exclusive lock on the source variable. Temp usage (inline args) does not lock.]
  [#*: #+ Stack temps: temp protocol instances are stack-allocated (no malloc/free).
    Named protocol variables remain heap-allocated via the create function.]
  #*: #+ 12 new tests (8 typecheck, 4 emitter including ASan). Total: 453 tests.

#---: Phase 26: Generics (Type Parameters and Monomorphization) \[COMPLETE\]

Added generic type parameters with constraints for records, unions, and
functions. Strategy: monomorphization (generate specialised code for each
concrete type used). Scope: records, unions, and functions only; classes and
protocols with generics are deferred to later phases.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Resolve #~"generic" type parameters: #~".generic" in
    #~"_resolve_dotted_path" creates #~"GENERIC_PARAM" marker types.
    Two-pass field resolution separates generic params from concrete
    fields. Added #~"generic_params", #~"generic_origin", #~"generic_args"
    to #~"ZType". Added #~"GENERIC_PARAM = 3" to #~"ZTypeType".]
  [#*: #+ Monomorphization engine: #~"_monomorphize" creates
    specialised copies of generic types with concrete args. Cache
    keyed by (template_name, concrete_args) avoids duplicates.
    Monomorphized types stored in #~"program.mono_types" for emitter.]
  [#*: #+ Constraint checking: concrete type verified against
    union constraint (subtypes must match).]
  [#*: #+ Generic unions: type parameters detected in pass 1,
    subtypes resolved in pass 2 with generic context. Tag generation
    deferred to monomorphization time.]
  [#*: #+ Generic records: two-pass resolution for generic
    fields. Construction with explicit type args supported.]
  [#*: #+ Generic functions: generic params detected in
    parameters. Resolution and return type handled in generic context.]
  [#*: #+ Call-site inference: #~"option.some 42" infers t=i64.
    #~"option.none i32" uses explicit type arg for null subtypes.]
  [#*: #+ Emit C for monomorphised types: generic templates
    skipped; monomorphized types emit tag enum + struct + destructor
    with mangled names (e.g., #~"z_option_i64_t").]
  [#*: #+ Added #~"option" union to #~"system.z" as a generic
    union with #~"some: t" and #~"none: null" subtypes.]
  [#*: #+ Written #~"examples/generics.z": generic union usage,
    match on generic types, system option type.]
  [#*: #+ Test suite: 13 typechecker tests + 8 emitter tests
    covering resolution, instantiation, caching, emission, ASan.]

Phase 26b: Generic inference gaps and partial instantiation:

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Error on unmonomorphized generic use: using a generic type
    without type args in a value context (#~"_check_operation") now emits
    #~"Cannot infer type arguments" error instead of silently producing
    invalid types. Covers zero-arg records, classes, and union subtypes.]
  [#*: #+ Inference from value args: #~"_infer_generic_record_construction"
    rewritten with field-to-generic-param mapping. Infers generic params from
    value arg types (e.g. #~"myrec x: 42" infers #~"t=i64"). Detects
    conflicts between explicit and inferred types.]
  [#*: #+ Error on fallthrough: #~"_check_call" returns #~"None" after
    failed generic inference instead of falling through to non-generic path.]
  [#*: #+ Generic type references in type position: call syntax
    #~"(myrec t: i64)" in field type positions resolves via new
    #~"_resolve_typeref_call". Error on bare generic type names.]
  [#*: #+ Partial instantiation: #~"(myrec t: u)" where #~"u" is an
    enclosing generic param produces a new generic template (#~"myrec_u"
    with #~"isgeneric=True"). #~"_monomorphize" detects #~"GENERIC_PARAM"
    args and preserves genericity. Partial types are not registered for
    emission.]
  [#*: #+ Recursive child monomorphization: when a parent type is fully
    monomorphized, partially-instantiated children are recursively resolved
    (e.g. #~"wrapper_i64.inner" becomes #~"myrec_i64").]
  #*: #+ 13 new tests (8 inference, 5 partial instantiation). Total: 649 tests.

Deferred to future phases:

#ul:
  #*: #+ #~"generic from: X" call syntax
  #*: #+ Classes and protocols with generic parameters
  #*: #+ #~"any.valtype" / #~"any.reftype" constraint subtypes


#---: Phase 27: Owned Protocol Creation (Post-Generics) \[COMPLETE\]

Depends on Phase 26 (generics): uses #~"T from: myprotocol" generic constraint.

Add owned protocol instances via #~"myprotocol.create from: obj.take". The
#~"from:" parameter accepts any type that has declared conformance to the
protocol. Uses generics: the #~"create" function is generic over
#~"T from: myprotocol" (constrained by protocol conformance). The compiler
generates monomorphized #~"create" variants per conforming type. Each variant
boxes the data (copies for records, takes pointer for classes), sets the
appropriate vtable and destroy function.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Define #~"create" as a synthetic method on protocol types:
    #~"create: function {from: T.take} out myprotocol" where #~"T" is checked for
    conformance to the protocol.]
  [#*: #+ Generate per-conforming-type #~"create_owned" that allocates,
    copies/takes the data, and sets vtable + destroy.]
  [#*: #+ Ownership: #~"from:" accepts #~".take" (owned transfer). The protocol
    instance owns the boxed data and frees it via the destroy function pointer.]
  [#*: #+ Emit C: each #~"create_owned" allocates protocol instance + boxed data,
    sets vtable and destroy. The destroy function frees the allocation.]

Phase 27b: add 'take' and 'borrow' as compiler generated methods on the created
protocol instance.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ #~"take" is an alias for the already implemented #~"create"
    method. It has the same signature "take: function {from: T.take} out myprotocol".]
  [#*: #+ #~"borrow" creates a borrowed protocol instance from a locked source:
    "borrow: function {from: T.lock} out myprotocol". The source variable is
    locked exclusively for the lifetime of the protocol instance.]
  [#*: #+ #~".lock" compiler method added as explicit lock annotation on arguments
    (alias for #~".borrow").]

#---: Phase 28: Generic Tag Type \[COMPLETE\]

Depends on Phase 26 (generics): #~"tag" becomes generic parameterized by
discriminator type.

After generics are implemented, replace the current #~"tag" placeholder
record with a proper generic type. The #~"tag" type should be parameterized
by the discriminator storage type (e.g. #~"tag(u16)"). The #~"x: tag myenum"
syntax inside an #~"is" block can also be supported at that time.

#ol:
  #*: #+ Define #~"tag" as a generic type in #~"system.z".
  #*: #+ #~"data.tag" returns #~"tag(element_type)" (monomorphized tag record).
  #*: #+ #~"u16.tag" returns generic #~"tag" (recognized by union/variant processing).
  [#*: #+ Replace TAG type creation with monomorphized tag records
    (#~"generic_origin = \"tag\"").]

#---: Phase 29: Typedefs (Wrapper Types) \[COMPLETE\]

The grammar has been changed: an item_definition can no longer take a bare
operation, it must always take a series of child definitions in braces.

Add typedef support. Typedefs wrap an underlying type with zero overhead. A
typedef is created by using a standard object definition (class, record, union,
variant). In the 'is' section is a single named item that refers to the
'typedef' of the underlying type. eg. "mybase: basetype.typedef". 'mybase' can
be any name provided by the user.

Kind matching is strict for like types: class wraps class, record wraps record,
union wraps union, variant wraps variant. Protocols and facets cannot have their
own typedef syntax (no 'items' in their grammar), so class is also used to
create typedefs over protocols (both are reftypes) and record is used to create
typedefs over facets (both are valtypes). This avoids grammar changes for an
edge case.

'typedef' is a synthetic member that the compiler adds to all types to signify
that this is a typedef. It can only be used in the definition of a typdef item.

Similar to other features (such as 'tag'), 'typedef' is also a top level
predefined type that takes a generic 'any' parameter called 'from'. So the
definition could also have been 'mybase: typedef basetype'.

On the resulting typedef created by the compiler, 2 compiler generated
constructor methods are created. 

1. 'take' and 'create' are aliases for the same constructor that will take
ownership of the item of the basetype. signature is 
#~"take: function {from: T.take} out typedeftype"

2. 'borrow' is a constructor that will return a borrowed typedeftype while
taking a lock over the underlying basetype. Signature: 
#~"borrow: function {from: T.lock} out typedeftype.borrow"

There is older documentation that refers to a different way of creating
typedefs but it is obsolete, remove that. Ensure that all documentation is
consistent and complete as the feature is described here.

Other details:

#ul:
  [#*: #+ A typedef is a typesystem modification only, it does not affect the
    original object definition and is zero overhead at runtime.]
  [#*: #+ Compiler returns an error if the typedef object type is not the same as
    the object type specified in 'is' (eg typedef type is class but 'is'
    basetype is record). Strict kind matching: class-class, record-record,
    union-union, variant-variant.]
  [#*: #+ Class typedef also accepts protocol base types (both are reftypes).
    The class kind check allows class or protocol as the base type.]
  [#*: #+ Record typedef also accepts facet base types (both are valtypes).
    The record kind check allows record or facet as the base type.]
  [#*: #+ The typedef is a new type that is backwards compatible but not forwards
    compatible ie. the new type can be passed to existing functions that expect
    the old type but functions that require the new typedef'd type cannot be
    passed the underlying type.]
  [#*: #+ There can only be 1 #~".typedef" included in the 'is' section (in fact,
    only 1 definition in 'is' of any type for a typedef) else error.]
  [#*: #+ New methods can be added in the typedefs 'as' section. The new methods
    may shadow/replace existing method on the underlying object.]
  [#*: #+ If access is required to the old methods that are being shadowed, this
    can be done by accessing the methods on the named base type from the 'is'
    section ('mybase' in the example above). Or they could be accessed on the
    type of the mybase type itself, with the 'this' argument passed in as the
    first argument.]
  [#*: #+ All new methods plus all unshadowed methods of the base object are
    exposed to the user of the new typedef'd item.]
  [#*: #+ The name given to the typedef in the 'is' section allows access
    to all methods on the underlying type as usual (and none of the new methods).]
  [#*: #+ Typedef generic parameters: all generic params of the underlying type
    must appear in the #~"typedef" field definition. They must also be redeclared
    in the 'as' section of the typedef type. There can be no additional generic
    types beyond those used in the underlying basetype, as there would be nowhere
    to specify them, since the compiler controls generation of the constructors
    and handles conversion from the underlying type.]
  [#*: #+ Null method hiding: setting a method to null in the 'as' section
    hides it from the typedef, producing an error if called.]
  [#*: #+ Typedef chaining: a typedef of a typedef is supported with
    compatibility chain walking.]
  [#*: #+ Expand test suite: resolution, type identity, method shadowing,
    null hiding, constructors, backward/forward compatibility, typedef chaining
    (10 type checker tests).]
  [#*: #+ Emit C for typedef: no separate struct emitted. Typedef emits as the
    underlying C type (zero overhead). Methods emit with the typedef-mangled
    name. Typedef create/take/borrow are identity operations (just emit the
    from: argument). Parameter and return types resolve through typedef chains
    to the base C type.]
  [#*: #+ Emit C for typedef method calls: call sites use typedef method name.
    Function pointer typedefs and forward declarations emitted for typedef
    as-functions. Self parameter resolves to base C type.]
  [#*: #+ Write #~"examples/typedefs.z": valtype and reftype typedefs with
    methods. Must compile and run.]

#---: Phase 30: Implement 'facet' \[COMPLETE\]

Implement the 'facet' type. It is a valtype interface type. It should be very
similar to 'protocol' (except is a valtype).

Files: #~"src/zast.py", #~"src/zparser.py", #~"src/ztypechecker.py",
#~"src/ztypecheck.py", #~"src/zemitterc.py", #~"tests/test_parser.py",
#~"tests/test_typecheck.py", #~"tests/test_emitter.py",
#~"examples/facets.z", #~"doc/spec.pdoc"

#ul:
  [#*: #+ Implement facet: Facet AST restructured to match Protocol
    (parameters, specs, includes). Parser updated to use protocol-style
    parsing (#~"_getobjectbody"). #~"FACET = 58" added to #~"ZTypeType".
    Type checker: #~"_resolve_facet_type" resolves specs, generic params,
    and synthesizes create/take/borrow constructors. Conformance checking
    reuses protocol infrastructure (#~"_process_as_items_protocols").]
  [#*: #+ Facet can also be used as a generic constraint, same as protocol.
    Added FACET to generic type lists in type checker.]
  [#*: #+ Instances of the facet are as large as the largest object that
    supports it + a pointer to the method table. C layout uses a union of
    all conforming types (#~"z_name_data_u") for automatic size and
    alignment. Vtable pointer is first field (constant offset). Facet
    struct emission is deferred to after all conforming types are defined.]
  [#*: #+ Creating a facet instance embeds a copy of that valtype within the
    facet instance. The #~"create_owned" function copies the value into the
    inline data union and sets the vtable pointer.]
  [#*: #+ Facet has 'take' and 'borrow' constructor same as 'protocol', but
    both take a copy. Borrow still locks the source for ownership
    consistency with protocols in generic code.]
  [#*: #+ Facet can only be implemented on valtypes (unlike 'protocol' which
    can be on any type). Error produced for classes/unions.]
  [#*: #+ The facet label in the 'as' section of an implementing type triggers
    conformance checking and generates wrapper functions, static vtable, and
    create function — same pattern as protocol.]
  [#*: #+ A facet can be the base type in a typedef (against a record parent
    type) same as protocol can be a typedef (against a class parent type).]
  [#*: #+ Tests: 3 parser tests, 9 type checker tests, 5 emitter tests
    (struct generation, create+dispatch, valtype semantics, function param,
    multiple conformers). 756 tests passing.]
  [#*: #+ Example: #~"examples/facets.z" demonstrating facet definition,
    multiple conforming records, facet creation, method dispatch, and
    facet as function parameter. Compiles and runs correctly.]
  [#*: #+ Documentation: #~"doc/spec.pdoc" facet section updated with full
    spec (conformance, constructors, runtime layout, generic constraints,
    typedef base). Removed "deferred" marker.]


#---: Phase 31: Numeric generics (parameterized by value) \[COMPLETE\]

Allow generic types to be parameterized by numeric values using the existing
#~".generic" syntax with numeric type constraints (e.g. #~"size: u64.generic").

#ol:
  #*: #+ ZType additions: #~"numeric_generic_params" set and #~"numeric_value" field
  [#*: #+ Detection: all 6 generic detection sites (function, class, union, record,
    protocol, facet) detect numeric constraints via NUMERIC_RANGES]
  [#*: #+ Resolution: #~"_resolve_numeric_generic_arg" parses literal, validates range,
    returns value-carrying ZType with mangled name]
  #*: #+ Typeref call: #~"_resolve_typeref_call" routes numeric params to numeric resolver
  [#*: #+ Record/union construction: #~"_infer_generic_record_construction" and
    #~"_infer_generic_union_construction" route numeric params to numeric resolver]
  [#*: #+ Monomorphization: skips type constraints for numeric params, auto-synthesizes
    fields for unreferenced numeric params, sets #~"param_defaults"]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: pre-registration populates #~"_type_field_defaults" from
    #~"param_defaults" for numeric generic fields]
  #*: #+ Example: #~"examples/numeric_generics.z"
  #*: #+ Tests: 10 typecheck tests + 3 emitter tests
  #*: #+ Documentation: spec and roadmap updated

This is required to implement arrays (Phase 33).

#---: Phase 32: Code deduplication with AST content hashing \[COMPLETE\]

Monomorphized generic methods are deduplicated at the AST level during type
checking, making it backend-independent. Functions are content-addressable
over their typed AST form using SHA-256 hashes.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Method body typechecking: non-generic record, class, union, and variant
    methods now have their bodies typechecked during type resolution (previously
    only signatures were resolved)]
  [#*: #+ AST content hasher (#~"zasthash.py"): SHA-256 hash of function structure
    including parameter types, return type, and body AST. Excludes function name;
    uses structural hashing for #~"this" parameter type]
  [#*: #+ Clone and dedup during monomorphization: method AST is deep-copied from
    the template, typechecked with concrete types in generic context, hashed, and
    deduplicated against a hash table. Duplicates become aliases]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: reads #~"program.func_aliases" dict; emits #~"#define" aliases
    for deduplicated methods instead of full function bodies]
  [#*: #+ Bug fix: #~"parse_number" now catches #~"ValueError" for invalid numeric
    literals (e.g. #~"0bool") instead of crashing]
  [#*: #+ Bug fix: #~"_resolve_typeref" now sets #~"path.type" when resolving
    #~"this" keyword]
  #*: #+ Tests: 7 AST hash tests + 4 dedup emitter tests
  #*: #+ Documentation: roadmap and compiler overview updated


#---: Phase 33: arrays (valtype, static length) \[COMPLETE\]

Implement arrays. Arrays are a valtype that are generic over the element types
AND their length. This means that arrays of different lengths are different
types, even if their element types are the same.

Arrays are part of the zerolang standard library but are not a builtin type. We
need a array unit in the lib. Constructor is 'array.create of: type to: x'
where 'type' is the type of each element which must be a valtype with an empty
('0') constructor. And 'x' is the size of the array (element indexes are 0 to
x-1).

Arrays are:

#ul:
  [#*: fixed length]
  [#*: valtype, the whole array can be replaced by another array of the same
  type and length]
  [#*: array is in the collections unit as part of the standard library]
  [#*: array is also aliased in core... array: collections.array]
  [#*: 'data' can be copied into a new array of the same type and length (data
  has a .array method)]
  [#*: the element indexes of the array are integers]
  [#*: 'array.0' gets the zeroth element. This is compile time checked (since
  we know the length of the array)]
  [#*: 'array.0: 1' sets the zeroth element, again, compile time checked for bounds]
  [#*: array.get(x) returns an optional of the xth element. x is a runtime
  variable and may exceed the length of the array, so there is runtime checks]
  [#*: array.set(x, val) sets the xth element to val. Returns true if
  successful (false if out of bounds]
  [#*: arrays of numeric types are initialised to 0]
  [#*: arrays of record types are initialised using the constructor if it has a
  constructor with default values (can be called with no arguments). If the
  constructor requires arguments, the compiler throws a type error]
  [#*: arrays of variants are initialised to the 0 type (if possible), eg
  boolean false. If it is not possible, the compiler throws a typeerror]

Completion steps:

#ul:
  [#*: #+ #~"lib/system/collections.z" -- array record definition]
  [#*: #+ #~"lib/system/core.z" -- array alias: collections.array]
  [#*: #+ Type checker: array monomorphization with valtype validation]
  [#*: #+ Type checker: compile-time bounds checking for array.N access]
  [#*: #+ Type checker: synthesized .get, .set, .length methods]
  [#*: #+ Type checker: data.array method for copying data into arrays]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: array struct with fixed-size data buffer]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: zero-initialized create constructor]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: .length #define constant]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: .get method (returns option, heap-allocated)]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: .set method (takes pointer, returns bool)]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: literal index access (a.0 → a.data\[0\])]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: literal index set (a.0 = val → a.data\[0\] = val)]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: data.array copy emission]
  [#*: #+ Set syntax: a.0 = 1 (reassignment, not a.0: 1)]
  [#*: #+ Length access: .length constant field (not .to)]
  [#*: #+ #~"examples/arrays.z" -- array example program]
  [#*: #+ Tests: 11 type checker tests, 13 emitter tests]

