#---: Phase 43: for-expression improvements \[COMPLETE\]

The #~"for" expression has several unimplemented features from the spec.

#----: 43.1 Post-conditions (do-while) \[COMPLETE\]

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Fix emitter to generate #~"do { body } while (postcond);" for
    pure post-condition loops (#~"for loop { body } while cond")]
  [#*: #+ For combined pre+post conditions, use break pattern:
    #~"while (pre) { body; if (!(post)) break; }"]
  [#*: #+ Fix parser to allow #~"for loop { }" without pre-conditions
    (was blocking on first-flag not being reset after loop body)]
  [#*: #+ Fix #~"break" and #~"continue" emission — handle as
    #~"AtomId" in #~"_emit_expression_stmt()" (was being mangled to
    #~"v_break" / #~"v_continue" instead of C keywords)]
  [#*: #+ Tests: do-while, do-while-once, pre+post, multiline do-while,
    infinite loop, break in loop, continue in loop (7 new tests)]

#----: 43.2 Iterator protocol \[COMPLETE\]

The iterator "protocol" is simply methods and callable object.

A callable object is an object that has a 'call' method. The compiler
determines if the syntax represents a call (with 0, 1, or many arguments) and
if the target/receiver of that call is an object (rather than a
function/method) then the compiler checks if the object has a 'call' method and
implicitly uses that method as the method being called.

An iterable object is one that has a method that returns an iterator callable
object. The method returning this is called 'iterate' by convention, but it can
have any name. The iterate method will lock the object being iterated and will
return a borrowed iterator object.

The iterator object itself will usually be constructed (from the parent object)
so that it locks the parent object that is passed to it. The parent object may
also pass its private (internal) API so that the iterator has full access to
the parent internals (public / private to be implemented in a later phase).

The iterator object is callable and returns an optional value. Once the
iterator is exhausted, it returns the 'none' option. The iterator may also have
arguments - for implementing a coroutine style iterator. But no arguments is
the common case.

The 'for' loop can only be bound to an iterator like object/function (that
returns an option). The iterator must be extracted from the iterable object
explicitly (at this stage, may change in the future if a less verbose syntax is
required). Retrieving the iterator would usually be done with a 'with'
statement. So full syntax would look similar to:

"with i: myiterable.iterate for x: i loop { ... }"

'i' becomes the iterator and within the loop body, 'x' is bound to the current
'some' value of the option. If the iterator returns 'none', 'x' is not bound
and the loop terminates.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Callable objects: type checker (#~"_check_call") detects when a
    variable (not a type name) is called and the variable's type has a
    #~"call" child method. Redirects dispatch through #~"CallKind.CALLABLE",
    skips the #~"this" parameter for argument matching. Emitter generates
    #~"z_type_call(receiver, args)".]
  [#*: #+ For-loop iterator bindings: #~"_check_for" detects when a named
    binding's operation returns #~"option" (directly, via a callable
    object's #~"call" method, or via a function's return type). Marks the
    binding in #~"fornode.iterator_bindings". Unwraps #~"some" type for
    the bound variable. Emitter generates a #~"while(1)" loop that calls
    the operation each iteration, checks #~"TAG_NONE" to break, and
    dereferences #~"->data" for the unwrapped value.]
  [#*: #+ Generic return types in parens: #~"out (option t: i64)" now
    works for functions returning monomorphized generic types. The parser
    accepts parenthesized generic type instantiation in the #~"out" clause.]
  [#*: #+ Tests: callable objects (with and without extra args), iterator
    bindings with callable classes, empty iterators (9 new tests total
    across all 43.x sub-phases).]

#----: 43.3 for-as-expression (list comprehension) \[COMPLETE\]

Spec says: #~"for can be used as an expression. The result will be a
list of the final values of the loop statement." Depends on the list
collection type being fully operational.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Type checker (#~"_check_for"): after checking the loop body,
    inspects the last statement. If it is an #~"Expression" with a non-null
    type, monomorphizes #~"list of: elem_type" and sets
    #~"fornode.type" to the list type.]
  [#*: #+ Emitter (#~"_emit_for_expression_value"): allocates a list temp
    variable, emits the for-loop with a modified body
    (#~"_emit_for_body") that appends each iteration's last expression
    value via #~"z_list_ELEM_append". Returns the list variable.]
  [#*: #+ #~"_emit_expression_value" dispatches #~"For" nodes with a type
    to #~"_emit_for_expression_value".]
  #*: #+ Tests: basic comprehension with #~".each" producing a list.

#----: 43.4 Range iteration (#~"each") \[COMPLETE\]

All integers in zerolang support an 'each' 'method' that can be used to iterate
that number of times.

'each' takes a 'from' argument that has a default value of 0. So a standard
range iterator of myint.each will by default iterate from 0 to myint - 1.

The each method appears to support usual zerolang iteration (ie. returning a
callable that returns each value in turn) but the C emitter does not create all
of these objects and instead emits a standard C for loop over the integer
values.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Type checker (#~"_check_dotted_path"): when the child name is
    #~"each" and the parent type is an integer, synthesizes a function type
    with a #~"from" parameter and an #~"option" return type. Placed before
    the numeric dotted-path check so #~"5.each" is not misinterpreted as a
    numeric cast.]
  [#*: #+ Emitter (#~"_emit_for"): detects #~".each" on integers in
    iterator bindings (unwrapping #~"Expression" wrappers for parenthesized
    calls). Emits an optimized C #~"for" loop:
    #~"for (type v = from; v < n; v++)".]
  [#*: #+ Supports #~"from:" parameter: #~"(n.each from: k)" iterates from
    k to n-1. Default is 0.]
  [#*: #+ Tests: #~"n.each", literal #~"3.each", #~"each from:",
    zero-iteration #~"0.each".]

#---: Phase 44: Generic Units \[COMPLETE\]

Units can be generic, with type parameters declared in the #~"as" body.
Instantiation via assignment alias: #~"intmath: (mathops t: i64)".

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Type checker: detect generic params in unit body (DottedPaths
    to #~"any.generic"), mark unit as generic, push generic context for
    body definition resolution.]
  [#*: #+ Monomorphization: extend #~"_monomorphize" to handle UNIT types —
    substitute generic params in function children, clone function bodies
    via #~"clone_function", type-check cloned bodies with concrete types
    in symtab. Register in #~"unit_types" and #~"_cloned_methods".]
  [#*: #+ Call dispatch: in #~"_check_call", detect generic UNIT callee and
    redirect to #~"_resolve_typeref_call" for monomorphization.]
  [#*: #+ Emitter: skip generic unit templates via #~"_is_generic_template",
    emit monomorphized unit functions via #~"_emit_mono_unit", handle
    unit aliases in #~"_emit_assignment" (no-op) and #~"_get_callable_name"
    (resolve alias to actual type name).]
  [#*: #+ Spec fix: units have #~"as" not #~"is" in argument table.]
  [#*: #+ Tests and examples: 3 inline unit tests, #~"genericunit.z" example.]
  [#*: #+ File units: on-demand resolution via #~"_ensure_file_unit_resolved",
    file unit names resolvable in #~"_resolve_name" step 5, generic file
    unit templates skipped during emission. #~"_find_generic_defn" extended
    to find file unit definitions. Multi-file test and
    #~"genericfileunit.z" + #~"genmath.z" example.]

#---: Phase 45: Box type \[COMPLETE\]

Objects may be defined to be generic over 'any' which could be either a valtype
or a reftype when converted to a concrete type. To handle both situations in a
similar way, introduce a new generic type called 'box'.

#ol:
  [#*: 'box' has a generic parameter 't' of type 'any.generic' and a 'from'
  argument of type 't' which takes ownership]
  [#*: when used, if the 'from' argument of type 't' is a reftype, the 'box'
  returns that argument unchanged. This is a typesystem 'change' only. There is
  no runtime cost. In subsequent code, the 'new' variable can be used exactly
  as the original type could be used. The old variable name in invalid as is
  usually done when an argument is taken]
  [#*: when used, if the 'from' argument of type 't' is a valtype, an
  allocation is done to store that valtype and the new 'boxed' variable becomes
  a reftype. Destruction of the boxed type needs to free the underlying memory
  that was allocated]
  [#*: 'box' can also be used in normal concrete code as a simple way to
  convert a valtype into a reftype. Note that this could also be done be
  creating a 'class' with the reftype as a single field, which would give more
  control (can create your own methods and could control access to the
  underlying field)]

Implementation:

#ol:
  [#*: System definition: #~"box: class {} as { t: any.generic }" in
    #~"system.z", exported via #~"core.z"]
  [#*: Type checker: #~"_check_box_construction" handles #~"box from: val".
    For reftype T: call resolves to T directly (#~"BOX_PASSTHROUGH").
    For valtype T: monomorphized box type created as reftype with inner type's
    children copied for transparent access (#~"BOX_CREATE")]
  [#*: Emitter: #~"_ctype" returns pointer to inner valtype ctype.
    #~"_emit_mono_box" emits destructor (free). #~"_emit_box_create" emits
    malloc+copy. #~"_emit_box_passthrough" emits ownership transfer.
    Auto-deref in #~"_emit_binop_value" for boxed operands]
  [#*: Tests: type checker tests for valtype/reftype box, emitter tests for
    arithmetic, comparison, passthrough. #~"box.z" example]

#---: Phase 46: public / private accessibility \[COMPLETE\]

'public' and 'private' are predefined identifiers for controlling access to the
members (fields and methods) of objects.

#ol:
  [#*: public and private use a 'unit' construct to define their contents.]
  [#*: private is automatically defined by the compiler to always include all
  members of the current object. It cannot be redefined by the user]
  [#*: public is automatically defined by the compiler to always include all
  members of the current object but it can be redefined by the user]
  [#*: the user can redefine public by using a 'unit' keyword inline within the
  'as' section of the object, eg.
  #~"public: unit { method1: mymethod1 field1: myfield1 }"]
  [#*: resolution of definitions within the public definition is done in the
  usual way and would be expected to resolve to other fields/methods in the
  'is' and 'as' section of the current object]
  [#*: it would be expected that the shortened label declaration syntax would
  often be used, but it would not be required if the user wanted to expose a
  method/field publicly with a different name to the interal declaration.
  Example of public with shortened syntax: #~"public: unit { :method1 :field1 }"]
  [#*: inside the object, the 'this' definition always accesses the 'private'
  namespace and can access all methods/fields]
  [#*: 'this.private' can also be passed to an external function or object
  definition. This allows creation of 'friend' objects similar to C++ that can
  share access to the internals of an object. Note that both the receiver must
  declare that it is receiving mytype.private as a parameter definition and
  only the mytype object itself can pass this.private. There is no way to gain
  access to the internals of an object without its cooperation]
  [#*: from outside an object, only members listed in the 'public' definition
  can be accessed. Remember that by default, this is all fields/members. But if
  declared explicitly can be a subset of available methods and may have
  different names than the internal members]
  [#*: 'public' could also be a useful tool for managing backwards
  compatibility. Members can be freely renamed internally while keeping the can
  external 'API'. Both the new name and the old name could be exposed in the
  public interface']
  [#*: 'public' also applies to 'unit's for controlling access to definitions
  within it.]
  [#*: otherwise, 'public' and 'private' can be applied to all instantiable
  object types: record, class, union, variant, protocol, facet]

Implementation:

#ol:
  [#*: Parser: #~"_getobjectbody" extended to handle inline #~"unit" definitions
    in #~"as" blocks (for #~"public: unit { ... }"). Extern references from
    the public unit are not promoted (resolved by type checker instead)]
  [#*: Type system: public_members (optional set of strings) field on
    #~"ZType". None = all-public (default). Set during type resolution
    when #~"public: unit { ... }" is declared in the #~"as" block]
  [#*: Type checker: #~"_extract_public_members" helper extracts member names
    from #~"as_items". Called from #~"_resolve_class_type",
    #~"_resolve_record_type", #~"_resolve_union_type",
    #~"_resolve_variant_type". #~"_is_non_public_access" checks external
    member access against #~"public_members", allowing #~"this" and
    same-type access]
  [#*: Emitter: no changes needed (zero-overhead compile-time enforcement)]
  [#*: Tests: type checker tests for default-public, restriction, error on
    non-public, this-access, class restriction, private redefinition, public
    renaming. Emitter tests for compilation. #~"visibility.z" example]
  [#*: Private redefinition prevention: error on #~"private: unit { ... }" in
    as blocks]
  [#*: Public renaming: #~"public: unit { api_name: internal_name }" redirects
    external access through the renamed public name to the internal member]
  [#*: Friend access via #~"this.private": implemented. A field declared as
    #~"mytype.private" grants the holder full access to all members of that
    type. Only code with internal access (methods of the type itself, or
    variables already holding a #~".private" reference) can pass
    #~"this.private". The #~".private" reference is always a borrow — the
    parent retains ownership. If the parent method returns a friend object
    (eg. an iterator), it should take a lock on #~"this" (eg.
    #~"{self: this.lock}") so the parent cannot be mutated or destroyed
    while the friend holds its reference. Zero runtime overhead — same C
    type, purely compile-time access control. Tracked via
    #~"ZVariable.is_private_access" and #~"ZType.private_fields".]


#---: Phase 47: C Runtime Library \[COMPLETE\]

Consolidate runtime C boilerplate into a dedicated Python module so the
boundary between runtime support code and user program code is clear, and
future extraction to a precompiled static library is straightforward.

#----: 47.1 Runtime module (#~"src/zemitterc_runtime.py") — stage 1

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Create #~"zemitterc_runtime.py" with pure functions (no AST
    access, no emitter state). All runtime C code lives here as string
    constants and builder functions.]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_runtime_includes()": emit conditional #~"#include"
    directives for required C standard headers]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_runtime_zstr()": emit #~"ZStr" struct, macros
    (#~"ZSTR_STATIC_FLAG", #~"ZSTR_SIZE", #~"ZSTR_IS_STATIC",
    #~"ZSTR_STATIC"), and helper functions (#~"zstr_new",
    #~"zstr_cat", #~"zstr_from_i64", #~"zstr_from_f64",
    #~"zstr_print", #~"zstr_free")]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_runtime()": orchestrator that returns all runtime
    support code (includes + ZStr runtime)]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_static_strings()": per-program #~"ZSTR_STATIC"
    literal declarations (program data, not runtime)]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_bounds_check()": container bounds-check with
    #~"fprintf"/#~"exit" (unsigned index, runtime length)]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_array_bounds_check()": signed-index bounds-check
    for fixed-length arrays (compile-time length in message)]
  [#*: #+ #~"emit_empty_check()": empty-container check with
    #~"fprintf"/#~"exit" (e.g. list pop)]

#----: 47.2 Emitter integration

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Update #~"zemitterc.py" to import #~"zemitterc_runtime" and
    delegate runtime code emission via #~"emit_runtime()" and
    #~"emit_static_strings()"]
  [#*: #+ Replace inline array bounds checks with
    #~"emit_array_bounds_check()" calls]
  [#*: #+ Replace inline list-pop empty check with
    #~"emit_empty_check()" call]
  [#*: #+ Delegate existing #~"_emit_bounds_check()" to
    #~"zrt.emit_bounds_check()"]
  [#*: #+ Verify all 1166 tests pass with zero output changes]

#----: 47.3 Future — stage 2 (not in this phase)

#ul:
  [#*: Extract #~"emit_runtime_zstr()" output to #~"runtime/zrt_string.c"
    / #~"zrt_string.h"]
  [#*: Create #~"runtime/zrt_memory.c" / #~"zrt_memory.h": wrapper
    allocators (#~"zrt_malloc", #~"zrt_free") for arena or GC backends]
  [#*: Create #~"runtime/zrt_error.c" / #~"zrt_error.h": bounds-check
    and error-exit helper functions]
  [#*: Build system: #~"Makefile" target to compile #~"runtime/*.c"
    into #~"libzrt.a" (static archive via #~"ar rcs")]
  [#*: Update emitter to #~"#include" runtime headers instead of
    inlining. Update compile/link step to link #~"libzrt.a".]
  [#*: Tie to #~"native" keyword: map fully qualified native names
    to runtime library implementations via name mangling convention]

Files: #~"src/zemitterc_runtime.py", #~"src/zemitterc.py",
#~"doc/roadmap.pdoc"


#---: Phase 48: Implicit return \[COMPLETE\]

The return call should only be required for early returns. When return is used
in the final expression location, it is optional. 'for', 'if' , 'with', 'match'
can already be used as an expression, so that naturally should also extend to
implicit return ie. the result of each of these can also provide the implicit
return value.

#ol:
  [#*: Typechecker: propagate expression types through #~"expr.type" and
    bare block (#~"Do") nodes so block values bubble up correctly.]
  [#*: Typechecker: validate implicit return — last expression type must
    match declared #~"out" type. Assignments produce #~"null" type and
    trigger a mismatch. Explicit #~"return" (#~"never") is excluded.]
  [#*: Typechecker: detect when all branches of #~"if" or #~"match"
    return #~"never", and propagate #~"never" as the expression type.]
  [#*: Emitter: emit bare blocks as expression values using the
    #~"_emit_branch_with_result" temp-variable pattern.]
  [#*: Emitter: detect implicit return candidate in function body and
    emit last expression as #~"return <value>" with scope cleanup.]
  [#*: Tests and documentation.]

Files: #~"src/ztypecheck.py", #~"src/zemitterc.py",
#~"tests/test_typecheck.py", #~"tests/test_emitter.py",
#~"doc/roadmap.pdoc", #~"doc/grammar.pdoc", #~"doc/spec.pdoc"


#---: Phase 48a: Match/case as expression value \[COMPLETE\]

Match expressions can now be used as values when exhaustive (all subtypes
covered or else clause present). Branch types are unified and checked for
compatibility. The emitter generates temp-variable patterns for all match
variants (simple enum, union switch, variant switch, nullable-ptr).

#ol:
  [#*: Typechecker: unify branch types in #~"_check_case" (parallel to
    #~"_check_if"). Gate on exhaustiveness.]
  [#*: Emitter: add #~"_emit_case_expression_value" with sub-methods for
    simple enum, union, variant, and nullable-ptr match patterns.]
  [#*: Tests and documentation.]

