#---: Phase 49e: Auto-Generated Equality for Value Types \[COMPLETE\]

Auto-generate == and != operators for all value types (records, variants,
arrays, str). Structural equality by default: field-by-field for records,
tag+payload for variants, element-wise for arrays, byte-wise for str.
User can override == in the #~"as" section or opt out with == set to null.

#ol:
  [#*: #+ Type checker: _synthesize_eq method synthesizes == and != as
    FUNCTION types in rtype.children for records, variants, and monomorphized
    types. Checks all fields/subtypes support == before synthesis. Skips if
    user-defined or null-hidden.]
  [#*: #+ C emitter: z_{name}_eq() static functions emitted for records
    (field-by-field), variants (tag+switch on payload), arrays (element loop),
    and str (memcmp). _emit_binop_value routes == and != to eq function calls
    instead of C operators.]
  [#*: #+ != always derived as !(a == b), not independently overridable.]
  [#*: #+ Function pointer fields compared by address (C == on raw pointers).]
  [#*: #+ #~"is_autogen_eq" field on ZType distinguishes auto-generated from
    native/user-defined operators.]
  [#*: #+ Tests: 9 type checker tests, 7 emitter tests covering records,
    variants, enums, nested types, null-hiding, user override.]
  [#*: #+ New example: #~"examples/equality.z" demonstrating record, variant,
    enum, and nested equality.]
  [#*: #+ Documentation: spec, FAQ, and roadmap updated.]
  [#*: #+ Renamed #~"is_memcmp_eq" to #~"is_simple_eq" -- semantic flag meaning
    equality is fully determined by byte representation (no floats, no user
    overrides). Emission strategy is an emitter concern, not a type property.]
  [#*: #+ Size threshold for memcmp: types larger than 16 bytes use memcmp,
    smaller types use field-by-field comparison (avoids memcmp call overhead).
    Threshold constant #~"_EQ_MEMCMP_THRESHOLD" in emitter. Size estimated from
    C field types via #~"CTYPE_SIZES" dict and #~"_estimate_type_size" method.]
  [#*: #+ Reference types have no default == (compile error). User must define
    explicitly. String is the exception: built-in content comparison via
    #~"zstr_eq" in C runtime.]
  [#*: #+ #~"identical" function: native generic function for reftype identity
    (pointer equality). Declared in #~"system.z", exported via #~"core.z".
    Currently special-cased in type checker; deferred: resolve through standard
    generic function inference when that feature is implemented.]

